<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-10">
  <title>Investigation 5.10: Running Out of Time</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-10" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <p>Data from a local 5K race include age and finish time for 248 runners. The goal is to assess whether finish time changes with age.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-a" label="I5.10.a"><title>Identify Variables</title><statement><p>(a) Identify explanatory and response variables.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The explanatory variable of interest here is age and the response variable is finishing time.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-b" label="I5.10.b"><title>Conjecture Direction and Form</title><statement><p>(b) Predict direction, linearity, and likely significance of association.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>We might expect older people to tend to be slower (larger finish times) so a positive association. Conjectures about form and strength will vary.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-c" label="I5.10.c"><title>Scatterplot and Data Features</title><statement><p>(c) Plot finish time vs age and discuss unusual features/outliers.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>We do notice a weak, positive, linear association between time and age. There is also an extreme outlier, a rather young runner who took almost 80 minutes. The outlier could be due to an injury during the race.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-d" label="I5.10.d"><title>Refit Without Outlier</title><statement><p>(d) Remove outlier and report regression equation and slope interpretation.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>With each one-year increase in age, we predict .1403 hours (about 8 minutes) to be added to the finish time, on average.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-e" label="I5.10.e"><title>Sampling-Variability Question</title><statement><p>(e) Could observed slope arise by chance if no population association exists? Outline investigation approach.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>It's possible. We need to know how unusual a slope of .1403 (or more extreme) is for a random sample of 247 runners from a population with no association.</p></solution></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Terminology Detour</title>
      <p>Use <m>b_0, b_1</m> for sample intercept/slope and <m>\beta_0, \beta_1</m> for population parameters.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-f" label="I5.10.f"><title>Hypotheses for Slope</title><statement><p>(f) State null and alternative hypotheses for testing whether finish time changes with age.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>This would imply a population slope of zero. <m>H_0</m>: no association between finish time (population slope = 0) and age vs. <m>H_a</m>: a positive association between finish time and age (population slope &gt; 0).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-g" label="I5.10.g"><title>Compute Sample Summaries</title><statement><p>(g) Obtain means, SDs, and regression residual SD from data.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Note: I removed the runner, not just the finishing time. <m>s\approx 8.265</m> min.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-h" label="I5.10.h"><title>Design Null Population</title><statement><p>(h) Build a null population with <m>\beta_1=0</m> and matching sample characteristics; draw one sample and compare slopes.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The sample regression line shouldn't exactly match the population regression line (<m>\beta_1=0</m>).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-i" label="I5.10.i"><title>Second Sample and Variability</title><statement><p>(i) Draw another sample; compare regression line and discuss sampling variability.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The sample regression line is expected to vary from sample to sample.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-j" label="I5.10.j"><title>Many Sample Lines</title><statement><p>(j) Draw many sample lines and describe variation pattern.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The lines form a criss-crossing pattern, like a bow-tie or cat whiskers.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-k" label="I5.10.k"><title>Null Distribution of Slopes</title><statement><p>(k) Describe shape, center, and SD of null slope distribution.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The shape should be symmetric with a mean around zero and a standard deviation of about 0.03.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-l" label="I5.10.l"><title>Expected Center</title><statement><p>(l) Is center as expected under null? Explain.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>We expect the average sample slope to be close to zero, the value of the population slope. This shows that the sample slope is an unbiased estimator of the population slope.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-m" label="I5.10.m"><title>Change Sigma</title><statement><p>(m) Reduce sigma and describe population scatterplot change.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The vertical distances from the points to the horizontal regression line will be smaller.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-n" label="I5.10.n"><title>Predict Effect of Sigma Change</title><statement><p>(n) Predict effect on slope distribution.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Conjectures will vary.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-o" label="I5.10.o"><title>Check Sigma Prediction</title><statement><p>(o) Simulate and evaluate prediction from part (n).</p></statement><response/><solution><p>There should be less sample-to-sample variability in the sample slopes (smaller standard deviation).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-p" label="I5.10.p"><title>Change SD(X)</title><statement><p>(p) Modify SD(X); predict effect on slope and intercept sampling distributions.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The horizontal distances from the points to the <m>\bar{x}</m> value will be smaller (less horizontal width to the population scatterplot). Predictions will vary.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-q" label="I5.10.q"><title>Check SD(X) Prediction</title><statement><p>(q) Simulate and evaluate predictions from part (p).</p></statement><response/><solution><p>There will actually be more sample-to-sample variability in the sample slopes (larger standard deviation).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-r" label="I5.10.r"><title>Change Sample Size</title><statement><p>(r) Reduce sample size and predict effect on slope distribution.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Might conjecture the sampling distribution to have less variability when the samples are based on larger sample sizes.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-s" label="I5.10.s"><title>Check Sample Size Prediction</title><statement><p>(s) Simulate and evaluate prediction from part (r).</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The standard deviation of the slopes should decrease.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-t" label="I5.10.t"><title>Summarize Effects</title><statement><p>(t) Summarize effects of sigma, SD(X), and n on slope sampling distribution.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>With a larger value of <m>\sigma</m>, there is more variability in the distribution of sample slopes.</p><p>With a larger value of <m>s_x</m>, there will be less variability in the distribution of sample slopes.</p><p>With a larger sample size, there will be less variability in the distribution of sample slopes.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-u" label="I5.10.u"><title>Intuition</title><statement><p>(u) Explain intuitively why these effects occur.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>When there is less variation away from the regression line, there will be less variation in the sample regression lines, it is more difficult to get "extreme" sample regression lines. When there is less variability in the explanatory variable, we are not given as much information about the relationship between the two variables and it will be easier to get more extreme sample results. Larger samples, as we often see, lead to less sampling variability in our statistic.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-v" label="I5.10.v"><title>Formula Consistency</title><statement><p>(v) Compare simulation behavior to formula for SD of slope estimator.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Yes, <m>n</m> and <m>s_x^2</m> are in the denominator and <m>\sigma</m> is in the numerator.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-w" label="I5.10.w"><title>Observed Slope Under Null</title><statement><p>(w) Locate observed slope in null distribution and estimate p-value.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Example results: 0.14 is in the tail of the simulated null distribution, it does not seem likely that if the population slope was zero we would observe a sample slope as extreme as 0.140 just by chance.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-x" label="I5.10.x"><title>Alternative Null Slope</title><statement><p>(x) Repeat simulation for a nonzero null slope and assess plausibility.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Example results: The distribution of sample means will now center around 0.10. Now the value of 0.14 is not so extreme. Here we found such a slope or larger about 10% of the time. The value of 0.10 appears to be plausible for <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></solution></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Study Conclusions</title>
      <p>These data typically provide strong evidence that finish time and age are associated in this runner population context; large observed slope values are highly unlikely under a no-association model.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-y" label="I5.10.y"><title>Estimate Sigma</title><statement><p>(y) Suggest how to estimate population residual SD from sample data.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Suggestions will vary, but can use the <m>s</m> value calculated earlier.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-z" label="I5.10.z"><title>Standardize Slope</title><statement><p>(z) Compute standardized slope statistic.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>By hand: <m>t=.14/.03\approx4.67</m>, which will have a small p-value (df = 247-2 = 245).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-aa" label="I5.10.aa"><title>Technology Confirmation</title><statement><p>(aa) Confirm t-statistic and p-value with technology output.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The technology uses 0.03128 as the value of the standard error rather than the estimate from the simulation.</p></solution></exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-practice-a" label="I5.10A"><title>Practice Problem 5.10A</title><statement><p>Repeat analysis without removing outlier and compare results.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-10-practice-b" label="I5.10B"><title>Practice Problem 5.10B</title><statement><p>Compare unofficial and official race files and reassess evidence strength.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
